.TH universal-argument 2
.XI universal-argument - "\*(C0Set the command argument count"
.SH NAME
universal-argument \- Set the command argument count
.Me $a
.SH SYNOPSIS
.na
\fBuniversal-argument\fR \*(C0
.ad
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B universal-argument
sets the argument  number passed to a command to 4^\fIn\fR (4 to the power of
\fIn\fR)  where  \fIn\fR is the  number of calls to  \fBuniversal-argument\fR,
e.g.   the   key    sequence    "\fC\*cu\*cn\fR"    moves    down   4   lines,
"\fC\*cu\*cu\*cu\*cn\fR" moves down 4*4*4 = 64 lines.
.PP
After  invoking  the  \fBuniversal-command\fR  a  '\fI-\fR'  character  can be
pressed to negate the argument value, and an alternative  numeric argument can
be entered using the '\fI0\fR' to '\fI9\fR' keys.
.PP 
Invoking this command via
.Ht execute-named-command  2
or by a macro has no effect. The  command  should be treated as a command  key
prefix (like
.Ht prefix 2 )
in that it may be bound to only one key  sequence  which  must be a single key
stroke.  Re-binding  this  command to another key unbinds the new key and also
the current \fBuniversal-argument\fR key.
.PP
The  \fBprefix 1\fR  key (by default  bound to \fCesc\fR)  may also be used to
enter a numeric  argument at the message  line, e.g. "\fCesc 1 0 C-f\fR"  will
move forward 10 characters.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.na
.Ht prefix 2 .
.ad
